avior.","test_description":"Create an integration test that (1) loads or mocks freshness rules in the same format as production (e.g., fixture matching config structure); (2) instantiates CacheLayer with these rules; (3) calls compute_ttl('user_profiles') and asserts result equals 300 seconds (5 min); (4) calls compute_ttl('product_catalog') and asserts 3600 seconds (1 hour); (5) tests missing category and invalid rule edge cases. Use a fixture that mimics the real config file format, not a string mock.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test exercises the full TTL path—rules loading and computation. This catches failures in both config loading and algorithmic logic, validating Integration level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failures include: (1) switching logic is inverted or off-by-one, (2) memory measurement doesn't trigger at the right threshold, (3) strategy doesn't actually change. A unit test with mocked memory usage catches (1) but misses (2)—mocking hides how memory is measured in context. An integration test must simulate or cause actual memory pressure (or use integration-level injection) in the context of cache operations to verify the switching happens correctly in response to real conditions.","test_description":"Create an integration test that (1) creates a CacheLayer with memory_threshold configured to 80% (or similar); (2) populates the cache with enough entries to approach or exceed threshold (either by adding many items, mocking memory via integration fixtures, or using patch.object in integration context); (3) monitors or triggers memory check; (4) verifies cache.current_eviction_strategy switches from 'LRU' to 'LFU'; (5) adds one more entry and v