l, which are the core behavior.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Real failures are purely algorithmic: wrong entry evicted (LRU removes MRU instead of LRU, or LFU removes most-frequent instead of least-frequent), or eviction doesn't happen. These failures are in the core logic and can be caught by a unit test that (1) fills a cache to capacity, (2) accesses entries in controlled order (LRU) or frequency patterns (LFU), (3) adds one more entry, (4) verifies the correct entry was removed. No infrastructure, no I/O, no external calls needed.","test_description":"Create unit tests for LRU and LFU separately: (LRU) create CacheLayer with max_size=2, add key1 and key2, access key1 (making it recent), add key3 (should evict key2 as least recent), assert key1 and key3 remain and key2 is gone. (LFU) create CacheLayer with max_size=2, add key1 and key2, access key1 multiple times (increasing frequency), add key3 (should evict key2 as least frequent), assert key1 and key3 remain. Test both eviction strategies, boundary cases (max_size=1, equal frequency), and verify the removed entry is actually deleted from memory.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test directly exercises eviction logic with controlled access patterns. No mocking or infrastructure is needed; the failure is in the eviction algorithm itself.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13335,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13335},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard